{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"358"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/358"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.05,0.2,0.01,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108821"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/358"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91184"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9084"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9275"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44752"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108821"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old woman presents with a three-week history of anorexia and weight loss. Over the last three days she has noticed yellowing of her skin and eyes, dark urine and pale stools. She had recently returned from a holiday in Bali and had been taking doxycycline for prevention of malaria. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 128/84 mmHg, pulse 84/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and Sp02 98% on room air. She has significant jaundice affected her skin and sclera. She has multiple scratch marks across her arms and chest. Her abdomen is soft, with no areas of tenderness. Bowel sounds are present and the liver span is of normal size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver function test results are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 293\u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;25)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase (ALP) 1914U/L (40-130)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma glutamyl transpeptidase (GGT) 859U/L (\u0026lt;50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum alanine transaminase (ALT) 361U/L (\u0026lt;51)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum aspartate aminotransferase (AST) 252 U/L (5 - 35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum albumin 31g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her illness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug-induced cholestasis","Cholangitis","Viral hepatitis","Liver abscess","Carcinoma of the pancreas"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPainless jaundice must always raise a suspicion for \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreatic cancer\u003C/strong\u003E until proven otherwise. Furthermore, from this history the unexplained weight loss and anorexia hint at a potential malignancy diagnosis. Pancreatic cancer causes obstructive jaundice when the mass becomes large enough to obstruct the bile drainage, resulting in a post-hepatic cholestasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile all of the conditions listed could cause jaundice, the biochemical picture is that of obstruction (very high GGT and ALP suggest post-hepatic obstruction) and that limits the likely diagnoses to one of the two post-hepatic problems; pancreatic cancer or cholangitis. What makes pancreatic cancer more likely is her age and the painless nature. Cholangitis is acute infection of the bile duct. Cholangitis presents with Charcot\u0027s triad of abdominal pain, jaundice and fevers/chills. She does not display any of these symptoms besides the jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurthermore, despite her recent trip to Bali and potential exposure to viral hepatitis, she does not display the typical flu-like symptoms, fever and abdominal pain. Her LFTs also do not reflect an acute hepatitis picture, where the AST and ALT would be more raised. Similarly, a liver abscess may create abdominal pain or discomfort and deranged ALT and AST more than GGT and ALP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDoxycycline can cause hepatocellular damage and hence jaundice, but this is rare and often occurs in combination with other medications. This patient\u0027s liver function tests reflect post hepatic obstruction rather than intracellular damage. Malaria can also cause jaundice, but she does not display the typical features of malaria and if she was taking doxycycline effectively she should have avoided this risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless jaundice must always cause concern for pancreatic cancer","Cholestasis causes raised ALP and GGT more than AST and ALT","Acute cholangitis can present with Charcot\u0027s triad of jaundice, fevers and abdominal pain"],"references":["Tang DM, Koh C, Twaddell WS, von Rosenvinge EC, Han H. Acute Hepatocellular Drug-Induced Liver Injury From Bupropion and Doxycycline. ACG Case Rep J. 2015 Oct 9;3(1):66-8. doi: 10.14309/crj.2015.103. PMID: 26504884; PMCID: PMC4612764.","Lindenmyer, C, 2020. Choledocholithiasis and Cholangitis. MSD Manual. Available from: https://www.msdmanuals.com/en-au/professional/hepatic-and-biliary-disorders/gallbladder-and-bile-duct-disorders/choledocholithiasis-and-cholangitis.","Loveday, B, 2019. Pancreatic Cancer. RACGP. Reprinted from AJGP Vol 48, NO. 12. Available from:  https://www1.racgp.org.au/getattachment/b5e918a3-4a41-43b5-a982-968300e23700/Pancreatic-cancer.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91184"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"358"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91184"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T16:02:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T16:02:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"358"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108821"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",